# pyrst standard library ‚Äî io
#
# A PURE-PYRST `StringIO` (CPython's `io.StringIO`): an in-memory, seekable
# text buffer. No external crate ‚Äî the whole module is pyrst source, embedded
# via `include_str!` (see `src/stdlib.rs`). Import as `from io import
# StringIO` (the FLAT form). The QUALIFIED form (`import io; io.StringIO(...)`
# / `s: io.StringIO`) does NOT work ‚Äî this is an ALREADY-documented compiler
# limitation, not new to this module: a qualified type annotation doesn't
# parse and a qualified CONSTRUCTOR call doesn't resolve (`module io has no
# function StringIO` ‚Äî classes aren't looked up through the qualified-call
# path, only module-level functions are), exactly as `random.Random` and
# `collections.deque` already document. `io` has no free functions to fall
# back on, so the qualified form is entirely unusable here (unlike `random`,
# which offers qualified free functions alongside its unqualified-only
# class).
#
# Dossier: docs/design/w2-dossiers/stringio.md (target fidelity 5/5, 32 parity
# cases). This module RE-ORACLED every claim it relies on against a live
# CPython 3 before committing to behavior below ‚Äî several dossier claims were
# refined or corrected in the process (see "RE-ORACLE CORRECTIONS").
#
# STATE ‚Äî one class, `StringIO`, over three fields:
#   buf: str        the whole buffer contents (getvalue() ignores position)
#   pos: int        the current read/write cursor (char-indexed, not byte)
#   _closed: bool   set True by close(); every I/O op raises ValueError after
#
# Public API (exact CPython names; signatures match CPython's REAL defaults,
# confirmed via `inspect.signature` ‚Äî e.g. `read`/`readline` default to `-1`,
# not `None`; `truncate` defaults to `None`). EXCEPTIONS (all forced by
# compiler-level gaps found while building this module ‚Äî see "COMPILER GAPS"
# below ‚Äî not stylistic choices):
#   - `StringIO.__init__`'s `initial_value` is REQUIRED, not defaulted
#     (gap #1).
#   - `truncate`'s `size` is a plain `int` with a sentinel default, not
#     `Optional[int] = None` (gap #2).
#   - `encoding`/`errors`/`newlines` are zero-arg METHODS (`s.encoding()`),
#     not `@property` attributes like CPython's `s.encoding` (gap #3).
#   class StringIO(initial_value: str)  # pass "" for CPython's `StringIO()`
#     - write(s: str) -> int
#     - read(size: int = -1) -> str
#     - readline(size: int = -1) -> str
#     - readlines(hint: int = -1) -> list[str]
#     - getvalue() -> str
#     - seek(pos: int, whence: int = 0) -> int
#     - tell() -> int
#     - truncate(size: int = <unset-sentinel>) -> int
#     - close() -> None
#     - flush() -> None
#     - writelines(lines: list[str]) -> None
#     - readable() -> bool / writable() -> bool / seekable() -> bool
#     - isatty() -> bool
#     - detach() -> (raises) / fileno() -> (raises)
#     - @property closed -> bool / @property line_buffering -> bool
#     - encoding() -> None / errors() -> None / newlines() -> None (methods)
#
# RE-ORACLE CORRECTIONS (dossier said X; live CPython 3.12 says Y):
#   1. truncate() position: the dossier's HAZARDS section claimed "truncate()
#      resets position to 0", and its BEHAVIOR MATRIX table listed `tell()`
#      as `0` after every truncate() probe. Live-checked: truncate() NEVER
#      changes `self.pos` ‚Äî every probed case in the dossier happened to have
#      `pos == 0` already (no seek before truncate), so the "0" was
#      coincidental, not caused by truncate. Confirmed with a seek-then-
#      truncate probe (`seek(8); truncate(3)` -> tell() stays 8). This module
#      implements "position unchanged" (which the dossier's own SURFACE table
#      row, not the HAZARDS prose, actually says).
#   2. `readline()` position on `StringIO("line1\nline2")` after two calls:
#      the dossier's BEHAVIOR MATRIX row claims "Position After: 12", but
#      `len("line1\nline2") == 11` ‚Äî 12 is out of range and impossible.
#      Live-checked: `tell()` is 11 after both readlines. Treated as a dossier
#      typo; the parity golden below uses the verified value (11).
#   3. `seek(pos, whence=2)` (seek-relative-to-end) also ONLY accepts
#      `pos == 0`, exactly like `whence=1` ‚Äî the dossier's ERRORS section
#      only demonstrated this for `whence=1`. A nonzero offset with
#      `whence=2` raises the SAME message text CPython uses for whence=1
#      (`"Can't do nonzero cur-relative seeks"` ‚Äî yes, CPython reuses the
#      "cur-relative" wording even for the end-relative case; verified
#      byte-for-byte against `io.StringIO`).
#   4. Closed-file error TEXT is not one uniform string: `read`/`readline`/
#      `write`/`seek`/`truncate`/`getvalue`/`readable`/`writable`/`seekable`/
#      `tell`/`line_buffering`/`newlines` all raise
#      `ValueError("I/O operation on closed file")` (no trailing period), but
#      `readlines()` and `isatty()` raise the SAME message WITH a trailing
#      period: `"I/O operation on closed file."`. This is a genuine CPython
#      quirk (two different internal check sites use different literal C
#      strings) ‚Äî verified with `repr(str(e))` on all of them side by side.
#      Reproduced exactly, including which methods get the period.
#   5. `flush()` NEVER raises, even on a closed StringIO (CPython's flush is
#      an unconditional unchecked no-op) ‚Äî not documented either way by the
#      dossier's ERRORS section, so it was live-checked directly.
#   6. `closed`/`encoding`/`errors` properties never raise, closed or not ‚Äî
#      also live-checked directly, not covered by the dossier's ERRORS list.
#   7. `readlines(hint)`: the dossier says "hint >= 0 reads approximate hint
#      bytes then stops"; live-checked precisely, the real rule is
#      `hint > 0` (strictly), not `hint >= 0` ‚Äî `readlines(0)` reads ALL
#      lines (confirmed: `StringIO("a\nb\nc").readlines(0) ==
#      ['a\n','b\n','c']`, matching the dossier's own probed case, but for
#      the reason "hint<=0 means unlimited", not "hint==0 happens to admit
#      everything"). Any `hint <= 0` (not just -1) means "read all"
#      (`readlines(-5)` and `readlines(-100)` also read everything).
#      Positive hints stop once the CUMULATIVE length of already-appended
#      lines STRICTLY EXCEEDS the hint (checked with `>`, NOT `>=`, after
#      appending each line ‚Äî an easy off-by-one: `StringIO("a\nb\nc")
#      .readlines(2)` returns `['a\n', 'b\n']` (TWO lines, cumulative 4),
#      not one, even though the running total already EQUALS 2 after the
#      first line. CPython-verified with `readlines(1)` (one line),
#      `readlines(2)`/`readlines(3)` (two lines), and a 5-line buffer's
#      `readlines(4)`/`readlines(5)`/`readlines(6)`/`readlines(7)` (three,
#      three, four, and four lines respectively)).
#   8. The dossier's "Complex Scenarios" row `StringIO("abc"); write("xy");
#      getvalue()` claims `'abcxy'` ("write appends when at end"). This is
#      simply WRONG: position starts at 0 for EVERY `initial_value` (the
#      dossier's own SURFACE table says so, and its own "seek()/tell()"
#      matrix row confirms `StringIO("hello").tell() == 0`), so writing at
#      an UN-seeked, freshly-constructed StringIO OVERWRITES from the start,
#      exactly like any other `pos == 0` write. Live-verified: `getvalue()`
#      is `'xyc'`, not `'abcxy'` ‚Äî reproduced in this module (and dual-run
#      matched against real CPython in examples/parity_io.pyrs).
#
# COMPILER GAPS (found while building this module, not previously documented
# anywhere in lib/*.pyrs ‚Äî no prior stdlib module had exercised either shape,
# so both had gone unobserved):
#   1. A CONSTRUCTOR call that OMITS a trailing default-valued parameter fails
#      to build (`argument #1 ... is missing` from rustc), even though the
#      identical pattern on a free FUNCTION or a METHOD works correctly
#      (verified: `def f(x: int = 5) -> int: ...; f()` builds and runs fine;
#      `class C: def __init__(self, x: int = 5): ...; C()` does NOT ‚Äî the
#      minimal repro isn't specific to `Optional`, generics, or this module).
#      Call-site default-fill is apparently wired for the function/method
#      call path but not the `ClassName::new()` constructor path.
#      Consequence: `StringIO.__init__`'s `initial_value` is a REQUIRED `str`
#      parameter here (see above), not the CPython-matching
#      `Optional[str] = None`.
#   2. A METHOD call passing a bare (non-`None`) value POSITIONALLY into an
#      `Optional[T]`-typed parameter fails to build (`expected Option<i64>,
#      found i64`), even though the identical bare value flows fine into an
#      `Optional[T]` parameter on a free FUNCTION call (verified:
#      `f(1, 2)` with `def f(x: int, y: Optional[int] = None)` builds; the
#      same shape as a METHOD, `c.m(5)` with `def m(self, y: Optional[int] =
#      None)`, does not ‚Äî only `c.m(y=5)` (keyword) or omitting the arg
#      entirely works for a method). Consequence: `truncate`'s `size`
#      parameter is typed as a plain `int` with an out-of-realistic-range
#      sentinel default (`-9223372036854775807`, i.e. i64::MIN + 1 ‚Äî a bare
#      `-9223372036854775808` literal does not lex, since pyrst parses the
#      sign and the magnitude separately and the magnitude alone overflows
#      i64; no valid CPython `truncate` argument is ever legitimately this
#      value) instead of `Optional[int] = None`, so the CPython-authentic
#      POSITIONAL call
#      shape `s.truncate(3)` keeps working (an `Optional[int]` parameter
#      would have forced callers into `s.truncate(size=3)`, itself a
#      divergence from real CPython, which is positional-only there).
#   3. A `@property` whose return type is `Optional[T]` is MISTYPED by this
#      compiler at every USE site. Minimal repro: `class C: @property\n def
#      val(self) -> Optional[str]: return None`, then in `main`,
#      `print(c.val)` fails to build (`Option<String>` doesn't implement
#      `Display` ‚Äî the print codegen didn't route it through the None-aware
#      print path it uses for a plain `Optional[str]`-typed local or a
#      REGULAR method's return value, both of which print `None`/the payload
#      correctly), AND `x: Optional[str] = c.val` ALSO fails to build
#      (wrongly re-`Some`-wraps an already-`Option<String>` value ‚Äî E0308
#      "expected String, found Option<String>"). Consequence: `encoding`,
#      `errors`, and `newlines` (CPython attributes that are always `None`)
#      are ordinary zero-arg METHODS here, called as `s.encoding()` rather
#      than CPython's bare `s.encoding`.
#   4. A `bool`-typed `@property`, when its access expression is printed (or
#      `str()`'d) DIRECTLY (`print(obj.prop)` / `str(obj.prop)`), prints in
#      Rust's native lowercase `true`/`false` instead of pyrst's
#      Python-style `True`/`False` that every OTHER bool-producing
#      expression uses (verified: an identical plain ‚Äî non-`@property` ‚Äî
#      method returning the same `bool` field prints `True`/`False`
#      correctly; `x: bool = obj.prop; print(x)` ALSO prints correctly ‚Äî
#      only the direct pipe into `print`/`str` is affected). `closed` and
#      `line_buffering` stay `@property` (matching CPython's bare-attribute
#      shape) since this is a PRINT-FORMATTING bug, not a build failure or a
#      wrong stored value ‚Äî assign to a local `bool` before printing/
#      stringifying (as this module's own dual-run parity golden,
#      examples/parity_io.pyrs, does) until it's fixed upstream.
#   5. THE MOST SERIOUS FINDING: `str.find(sub)` returns a Rust-native BYTE
#      offset, not CPython's CHAR (codepoint) offset ‚Äî verified minimal
#      repro: `"„Åì„Çì„Å´„Å°„ÅØ\nworld".find("\n")` returns `15` in pyrst (the
#      UTF-8 byte offset: 5 chars * 3 bytes) but `5` in CPython (the char
#      offset). Since this compiler's STRING SLICING (`s[a:b]`) IS correctly
#      char-indexed (separately verified), combining the two ‚Äî exactly what
#      `readline()`'s original `idx = rest.find("\n"); line = rest[:idx+1]`
#      did ‚Äî silently produces WRONG results (not a crash) for any non-ASCII
#      content preceding the match. This is a general `str.find` defect, not
#      specific to `io` ‚Äî `rfind`/`index`/`rindex`/`count` share the same
#      codegen shape (`src/codegen/exprs.rs`, the `"find"`/`"rfind"`/
#      `"index"`/`"rindex"`/`"count"` arms all call the Rust method
#      directly) and are LIKELY affected too, though only `find` was
#      actually re-verified here ‚Äî flagged for the integrator/compiler team
#      as the highest-priority follow-up from this card. Worked around
#      LOCALLY in this module with a hand-rolled char-indexed scan,
#      `_io_find_newline` (below), instead of `str.find`.
#
#   All five are compiler-level fixes outside a stdlib module's scope ‚Äî
#   flagged for the integrator/compiler team, not silently worked around
#   with a fake default or a silently-wrong call shape.
#
# DIVERGENCES (documented, not silently dropped):
#   - Runtime TypeErrors for wrong ARGUMENT TYPES (`StringIO(123)`,
#     `write(None)`, `read("5")`, `seek("1")`) are NOT reproduced: pyrst is
#     statically typed, so these calls are REJECTED AT COMPILE TIME instead
#     (a stronger, earlier failure than CPython's runtime TypeError). No
#     valid, type-correct call is affected.
#   - `bytes` initial_value (`StringIO(b"...")`) is out of scope ‚Äî pyrst has
#     no `bytes` type (G7).
#   - `StringIO.__init__(*args, **kwargs)`'s real C signature is variadic
#     (G4); modeled here as the one real parameter `initial_value: str`
#     (REQUIRED ‚Äî see "COMPILER GAP 1" above). Pass `""` for CPython's
#     `StringIO()` and the text directly for `StringIO("text")`; the
#     CPython keyword form `StringIO(initial_value="text")` also works
#     (kwargs bind constructor params by name).
#   - `truncate`'s sentinel-default `size` (see "COMPILER GAP 2" above) means
#     passing the literal `-9223372036854775807` explicitly would be
#     mis-read as "omitted" rather than raising `Negative size value
#     -9223372036854775807` like real CPython would. Not reachable by any
#     realistic caller (it is i64::MIN); documented rather than silently
#     ignored.
#   - KEYWORD ARGUMENTS ARE A DELIBERATE SUPERSET, not a gap: CPython's real
#     `_io.StringIO` methods are C-implemented and POSITIONAL-ONLY
#     (`inspect.signature` shows `(self, size=-1, /)` etc.) ‚Äî real
#     `s.read(size=2)` raises `TypeError: StringIO.read() takes no keyword
#     arguments`! pyrst's methods accept `size=`/`whence=`/etc as keywords
#     (kwargs v1), which is MORE permissive than real CPython, not less. Any
#     call written the way real code is actually written (positionally, or
#     omitting defaults) behaves identically either way.
#   - `io.UnsupportedOperation` does not exist in pyrst (no custom exception
#     classes ‚Äî G-exceptions). CPython's `detach()`/`fileno()` raise that
#     class, which is ITSELF a subclass of both `OSError` and `ValueError`;
#     this module raises the closest builtin, `OSError`, with the identical
#     message text (`"detach"` / `"fileno"`).
#   - `seek(pos, whence=1)`/`seek(pos, whence=2)` with `pos == 0` are
#     accepted as documented (no-ops that return the CURRENT position
#     unchanged for whence=1, or the end-of-buffer position for whence=2).
#   - `encoding`/`errors`/`newlines` are called as `s.encoding()` etc.
#     (methods) rather than CPython's bare `s.encoding` (attributes) ‚Äî see
#     "COMPILER GAP 3" above.
#   - `print(s.closed)`/`print(s.line_buffering)` (piped DIRECTLY into
#     print) render lowercase `true`/`false` rather than `True`/`False` ‚Äî
#     see "COMPILER GAP 4" above. Assign to a local `bool` first.
#
# FIDELITY: 4/5. Every I/O and positioning behavior in the dossier's 32
# parity cases, INCLUDING non-ASCII content (worked around at gap #5), is
# bit-for-bit CPython-identical after the corrections and workarounds above.
# The point below full marks is the accumulation of five real compiler-level
# gaps this card surfaced (none previously documented anywhere in
# lib/*.pyrs) ‚Äî the API-shape ones (`initial_value` arity, sentinel
# `truncate`, method-not-property `encoding`/`errors`/`newlines`, the
# bool-property print quirk) are cosmetic call-shape divergences with no
# behavioral effect on any call this module makes; `str.find`'s byte-vs-char
# offset bug (#5) is the one with real behavioral teeth, and it required an
# actual code workaround (`_io_find_newline`) rather than just a comment ‚Äî
# it is fully worked around WITHIN this module, but any caller outside it
# who reaches for `str.find`/`rfind`/`index`/`rindex`/`count` on non-ASCII
# pyrst strings should not assume char-offset semantics until it's fixed.

# NOTE: `truncate()`'s "not given" sentinel (`-9223372036854775807`, i.e.
# i64::MIN + 1 ‚Äî see "COMPILER GAPS" #2 above) is inlined directly at its two
# use sites below rather than factored into a module-level constant: this
# compiler's module-level-constant relaxation only accepts a BARE literal
# (`Expr::Int`/`Float`/`Str`/`Bool`) as the initializer, not a unary-minus
# expression (`-N` parses as `UnaryOp(Neg, Int(N))`), so a NEGATIVE
# module-level int constant does not build (another compiler-level gap worth
# flagging, found the same way as the two above ‚Äî no prior stdlib module had
# ever tried a negative module constant either).


def _io_find_newline(s: str) -> int:
    # A hand-rolled CHAR-indexed scan for "\n", used by `readline()` INSTEAD
    # of `s.find("\n")` ‚Äî see "COMPILER GAPS" #5 in the module header: this
    # compiler's `str.find` (and, presumably, `rfind`/`index`/`rindex`/
    # `count` ‚Äî not individually re-verified, but they share the same
    # codegen shape) returns a Rust-native BYTE offset, not a Python-style
    # CHAR offset, so it silently mis-indexes any search whose match is
    # preceded by a multi-byte character. `s[:idx]`-style slicing IS
    # correctly char-indexed (verified separately), so mixing the two
    # produces wrong results only on non-ASCII input ‚Äî caught by this
    # module's own dual-run parity golden on `"„Åì„Çì„Å´„Å°„ÅØ\nworld".readline()`
    # (pyrst returned `"„Åì„Çì„Å´„Å°„ÅØ\nworld"` whole, having computed a
    # `\n`-index of 15 ‚Äî the BYTE offset ‚Äî against a 16-char string, instead
    # of the correct char offset 5).
    n: int = len(s)
    i: int = 0
    while i < n:
        if s[i] == "\n":
            return i
        i = i + 1
    return -1


class StringIO:
    buf: str
    pos: int
    _closed: bool

    def __init__(self, initial_value: str) -> None:
        # REQUIRED, not `Optional[str] = None` ‚Äî see "COMPILER GAP" in the
        # module header: constructor calls do not fill an OMITTED
        # default-valued parameter in this compiler build (verified with a
        # minimal repro, not specific to Optional). Pass `""` for CPython's
        # no-arg `StringIO()` (empty buffer) ‚Äî behaviorally identical.
        self.buf = initial_value
        self.pos = 0
        self._closed = False

    def _check_open(self) -> None:
        if self._closed:
            raise ValueError("I/O operation on closed file")

    def write(self, s: str) -> int:
        self._check_open()
        buflen: int = len(self.buf)
        n: int = len(s)
        if self.pos >= buflen:
            pad: int = self.pos - buflen
            if pad > 0:
                self.buf = self.buf + ("\0" * pad) + s
            else:
                self.buf = self.buf + s
        else:
            self.buf = self.buf[:self.pos] + s + self.buf[self.pos + n:]
        self.pos = self.pos + n
        return n

    def read(self, size: int = -1) -> str:
        self._check_open()
        start: int = self.pos
        result: str = ""
        if size < 0:
            result = self.buf[start:]
        else:
            result = self.buf[start:start + size]
        self.pos = start + len(result)
        return result

    def readline(self, size: int = -1) -> str:
        self._check_open()
        start: int = self.pos
        rest: str = self.buf[start:]
        # `_io_find_newline` (a hand-rolled char scan), NOT `rest.find("\n")`
        # ‚Äî see "COMPILER GAP 5" in the module header: this compiler's
        # `str.find` returns a BYTE offset, not a CHAR offset, so it silently
        # mis-indexes any string with a multi-byte character before the
        # match (found while testing this exact method against
        # `"„Åì„Çì„Å´„Å°„ÅØ\nworld"`).
        idx: int = _io_find_newline(rest)
        line: str = ""
        if idx == -1:
            line = rest
        else:
            line = rest[:idx + 1]
        if size >= 0 and len(line) > size:
            line = line[:size]
        self.pos = start + len(line)
        return line

    def readlines(self, hint: int = -1) -> list[str]:
        # closed check raises WITH a trailing period ‚Äî one of the two
        # methods (with isatty) that use the other C-level message literal.
        if self._closed:
            raise ValueError("I/O operation on closed file.")
        result: list[str] = []
        total: int = 0
        while True:
            line: str = self.readline()
            if line == "":
                break
            result.append(line)
            total = total + len(line)
            # STRICT `>` (not `>=`) ‚Äî re-oracled: `StringIO("a\nb\nc")
            # .readlines(2)` returns TWO lines (`['a\n', 'b\n']`, total 4),
            # not one, even though the running total (2) already equals the
            # hint (2) after the first line. CPython only stops once the
            # cumulative length EXCEEDS the hint.
            if hint > 0 and total > hint:
                break
        return result

    def getvalue(self) -> str:
        self._check_open()
        return self.buf

    def seek(self, pos: int, whence: int = 0) -> int:
        self._check_open()
        if whence == 0:
            if pos < 0:
                raise ValueError(f"Negative seek position {pos}")
            self.pos = pos
        elif whence == 1:
            if pos != 0:
                raise OSError("Can't do nonzero cur-relative seeks")
        elif whence == 2:
            if pos != 0:
                raise OSError("Can't do nonzero cur-relative seeks")
            self.pos = len(self.buf)
        else:
            raise ValueError(f"Invalid whence ({whence}, should be 0, 1 or 2)")
        return self.pos

    def tell(self) -> int:
        self._check_open()
        return self.pos

    def truncate(self, size: int = -9223372036854775807) -> int:
        self._check_open()
        real_size: int = size
        if real_size == -9223372036854775807:
            real_size = self.pos
        elif real_size < 0:
            raise ValueError(f"Negative size value {real_size}")
        if real_size < len(self.buf):
            self.buf = self.buf[:real_size]
        # position is left UNCHANGED regardless of real_size (re-oracled ‚Äî
        # see "RE-ORACLE CORRECTIONS" #1 above).
        return real_size

    def close(self) -> None:
        # Idempotent: closing an already-closed StringIO is a no-op, matching
        # CPython (verified).
        self._closed = True

    def flush(self) -> None:
        # Unconditional no-op ‚Äî never raises, even when closed (re-oracled).
        return None

    def writelines(self, lines: list[str]) -> None:
        for line in lines:
            self.write(line)

    def readable(self) -> bool:
        self._check_open()
        return True

    def writable(self) -> bool:
        self._check_open()
        return True

    def seekable(self) -> bool:
        self._check_open()
        return True

    def isatty(self) -> bool:
        # closed check raises WITH a trailing period (re-oracled ‚Äî the other
        # of the two methods sharing that message variant, with readlines).
        if self._closed:
            raise ValueError("I/O operation on closed file.")
        return False

    def detach(self) -> None:
        # CPython raises io.UnsupportedOperation("detach") ‚Äî no such class in
        # pyrst; OSError is the closest builtin (UnsupportedOperation IS an
        # OSError subclass in CPython). Message text matches exactly.
        raise OSError("detach")

    def fileno(self) -> int:
        raise OSError("fileno")

    @property
    def closed(self) -> bool:
        # Never raises, open or closed (re-oracled).
        return self._closed

    @property
    def line_buffering(self) -> bool:
        self._check_open()
        return False

    # `encoding`/`errors`/`newlines` are METHODS here, not `@property` ‚Äî
    # see "COMPILER GAPS" #3 in the module header: a `@property` whose return
    # type is `Optional[T]` is mistyped by this compiler at every USE site
    # (`print(obj.prop)` fails to compile ‚Äî it emits a bare `Option<String>`
    # into a `{}` Display format slot instead of the None-aware print path ‚Äî
    # and `x: Optional[str] = obj.prop` fails to compile too, wrongly
    # Some-wrapping an already-`Option` value). `closed`/`line_buffering`
    # above are unaffected because they return plain `bool`, not
    # `Optional[T]`. CPython accesses these as bare attributes
    # (`s.encoding`, no parens); pyrst callers here must write `s.encoding()`.

    def encoding(self) -> Optional[str]:
        # Always None ‚Äî never raises, open or closed (re-oracled).
        return None

    def errors(self) -> Optional[str]:
        # Always None ‚Äî never raises, open or closed (re-oracled).
        return None

    def newlines(self) -> Optional[str]:
        self._check_open()
        return None
